# Testing Rules

## Framework
Vitest 4.x — config in `vitest.config.ts`, path aliases configured to match `tsconfig.json`.

## Commands
- `npm run test` — run all tests once
- `npm run test:watch` — run in watch mode

## Test Location
All tests in `tests/unit/`. Mirror source structure where useful.

## Existing Tests
- `tests/unit/dice.test.ts` — dice rolling, modifiers, advantage, result determination
- `tests/unit/quest-service.test.ts` — quest progression logic
- `tests/unit/turn-engine.test.ts` — turn advancement, round cycling
- `tests/unit/workers.test.ts` — AI worker fallbacks and output validation

## Test Structure Pattern
```typescript
import { describe, expect, it } from "vitest";

import { functionUnderTest } from "@/lib/path/to/module";

describe("functionUnderTest", () => {
  it("does specific thing when given specific input", () => {
    const result = functionUnderTest(input);
    expect(result).toBe(expected);
  });

  it("handles edge case", () => {
    expect(() => functionUnderTest(bad)).toThrow();
  });
});
```

## Mocking AI
Use `MockProvider` from `@/lib/ai/mock-provider` for tests that involve AI calls. It returns deterministic canned responses that conform to the expected Zod schemas.

```typescript
import { MockProvider } from "@/lib/ai/mock-provider";

const provider = new MockProvider();
```

## What to Test
- Pure logic functions (dice, turn order, stat calculations, HP clamping)
- AI worker fallback paths (call with broken input, verify fallback returns valid schema data)
- Zod schema validation (parse valid data, reject invalid data)
- Service functions with mocked DB (if feasible)

## What NOT to Test (for now)
- API route handlers directly (test via the services they call)
- React components (no component test setup yet)
- Pusher broadcast calls (side effect, mock in integration tests later)
